const CONTENT_WRITING_POOL = [
  {
    id: "science-fiction-last-of-us",
    title: "Separating science from fiction in The Last of Us",
    sourceUrl: "https://santinepillay.wordpress.com/2023/06/27/separating-science-from-fiction-in-the-last-of-us/",
    blocks: [
      { type: "attribution", text: "Written for Gush's blog.", linkText: "View the live version here.", href: "https://gush.earth/blogs/science/separating-science-from-fiction-in-the-last-of-us" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "This piece was written for Gush's blog. It served 2 purposes — to poise ourselves as opinion leaders, while also using SEO as a powerful tool. This creation utilised my expertise in pop culture while creating links to science, and life as we know it. It went through edits with the Scientific Officer who verified the independent research. The post was also adapted for Instagram and for our newsletter subscribers. #seriousbusiness #popculture" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Fungi seem fantastic. They do their thing in nature, give us wonderful things like bread, cheese, beer, truffle. Let's not forget the variety of mushrooms available from food-centric to psychedelic. There are millions of species. And as of late, fungi are getting a bad rep, courtesy of The Last of Us — a new \"zombie\" HBO show starring Pedro Pascal and Bella Ramsey, adapted from the 2013 video game. As fans of both the game and show, we found the scientific intricacies fascinating and worthwhile of discussion. Could fungi cause a global pandemic, control the minds of humans and cause the collapse of society? Let's find out." },
      { type: "heading", text: "The premise." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The Last of Us falls under the post-apocalyptic and horror genre. A mass fungal infection has spread across the world, turning people into zombie-like creatures hellbent on spreading till every last human is infected. It's a pandemic like no other, with no cure to be found. The fungus in question — are cordyceps. If that sounds familiar, it's because it's a common ingredient used in traditional Chinese medication to balance our yin and yang. No doubt fungi can be useful, but mutations are what we're worried about." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/science-fiction-last-of-us/3.png", alt: "Screenshot illustrating the fungal infection premise of The Last of Us" },
      { type: "heading", text: "How did the pandemic begin?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "In the TV show, the outbreak originated from a fungus outbreak in a flour and grain factory in Jakarta, Indonesia. These consumables were exported around the world, and infected people through ingestion. Yup, infection via pancakes and biscuits. It's stressful to think about." },
      { type: "heading", text: "But how does this even happen?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The pilot episode does an excellent job in melding real life science with fiction." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "It starts off with a talk show panel session in 1968 between 2 scientists who speak about pandemics. It posits that bacterial and viral pandemics are not the real threat — but fungal pandemics are. Fungi have the ability to not just kill, but to control. The scientists bring up a real world example of fungi taking control of an ant — using its body as a puppet. The ant isn't allowed to die or decompose. Instead, its mind is poisoned and its goal is simple: to spread to all ants." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Oof. Hard hitting stuff, only because it's true. Cordyceps primarily infect insects. It fills the host's cavity with mycelium and digests the non-essential parts of the host, keeping the insect alive. It then alters the behaviour of the host. In an episode of Planet Earth, David Attenborough narrates soothingly while we watch a zombie ant remove itself from the group, climb high, and eventually self-destructs — raining down spores that infect all the ants in the colony. It's real." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The panel session gets juicier. What about humans? Fungi cannot currently survive in our warm bodies, but that could change if global temperatures rise. Fungi could potentially evolve, adapt and survive. There's a chance that what happened to these ants, could happen to us. The scene ends with an uncomfortable silence, then cuts to the year 2003 where this has become a reality. It's the apocalypse, baby." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Let's unpack that. We know this: global warming and climate change are real. Global temperatures are rising. While there's no real evidence that fungi could infiltrate our bodies and act as puppeteers, it's not entirely improbable. Generally our body temperature protects us — a thermal barrier from fungal infections and diseases. The warming of the planet could allow fungi to adapt and affect humans. It cannot totally be ruled out. In fact, some types of fungi can survive in our bodies, causing lung diseases." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "If you have chills, so do we." },
      { type: "heading", text: "How does it spread?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "In the game, the infection is airborne — that is, it's spread through spores. Breathe them in, and you're in danger of turning into the undead." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/science-fiction-last-of-us/4.png", alt: "Screenshot referenced in the section on how the pandemic began" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "In the TV show, the infection is not necessarily airborne (yet). It's a tweak from the source material, so as to give full visibility of the cast's faces rather than wear gas masks the entire time. The infection is spread through bites and tendrils. Tendrils are a neural network that connect the infected by long fibres of underground fungus. Stepping on a patch of shrooms in one place will alert nearby infected of your location and you're pretty much doomed." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/science-fiction-last-of-us/5.png", alt: "Screenshot referenced in the section on real-life fungal science" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "In reality, we know spores can easily be inhaled into our lungs, causing issues that range from allergies, to serious illness, depending on your immunity. In biology, the term \"hyphae\" is used instead of Tendrils. They are a real underground neural network that create connections in nature between various plants, trees and fungi. They communicate and share nutrients to ensure the joint survival of nature." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The show does an amazing job using science as the basis to create a creative work of fiction." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Some fungal infections we know about." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/science-fiction-last-of-us/6.png", alt: "Screenshot referenced in the section on cordyceps and zombie ants" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "As we know by now, fungal infections can happen in many different ways beyond spores. Some fungal infections in humans are as follows:" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Thrush — caused by a yeast called Candida. Can be cured with antibiotics; fairly common; skin-related." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Candida Auris — When the Candida yeast takes a dangerous turn, it can cause infections in the mouth, genitals, ears, wounds, or worst of all, the bloodstream. This illness was first identified in Japan in 2009. It's difficult to diagnose, resistant to many anti-fungal drugs and can cause spread; spreads through contact, potentially airborne." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Aspergillosis — A mould infection in the lungs. It is likely we have all breathed in these spores without getting sick. Especially problematic with those with pre-existing lung issues. This type of mould commonly grows on walls, and spreads by airborne spores. Gush Interior Paints have been tested to resist Aspergillus growth." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Cryptococcal Meningitis — The biggest fungus-related killer of humans; airborne. When afflicted, it travels to the brain, causes inflammation, swelling, and results in death." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Should we be concerned about fungal infections?" },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/science-fiction-last-of-us/7.png", alt: "Screenshot referenced in the section on how the infection spreads" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The short answer is yes. It sounds like the fungal infections we know about are far and few between. That's because our bodies are well equipped with tools to fight these infections before it gets serious. It's likely that we've breathed in these spores before, and cleared them." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Despite this, researchers in this field have been worried about the possibility of fungal outbreaks for years now. Unlike viruses and bacteria, fungi mutate and spread slower. For these reasons, less time, money and energy is spent on research. We're missing a big caveat though. What about those who are immunocompromised? They are extremely susceptible. The diagnostics tools we have right now are limited — it's difficult to ascertain if an infection is of the fungal nature. By the time we correctly diagnose it, it's likely too late." },
      { type: "heading", text: "More research is needed." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/science-fiction-last-of-us/8.png", alt: "Screenshot referenced in the section on known fungal infections" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The WHO released a report in 2021 with a list of health threatening fungi. Currently, we only have 4 classes of anti-fungal medications available. Some fungi have already grown resistant to these medications. This places those who are immunocompromised at a very high risk." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Prevention is everything." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/science-fiction-last-of-us/9.png", alt: "Screenshot referenced in the section on fungal infection concerns" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "As individuals, we don't have the power to fund research or formulate miracle drugs. What we can do, is to stay informed and take precautions where we can. That's where Gush comes in." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Gush Interior Paints have been put through rigorous testing for its anti-moulding and anti-bacterial capabilities. As part of the SS150 test requirements for interior paints in Singapore, our paints were inoculated with Aspergillus niger and showed no mould growth for the duration of the test period." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/science-fiction-last-of-us/10.png", alt: "Screenshot referenced in the section on Gush's anti-mould paint testing" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Beyond that, we've tested our paints in local malls — particularly areas located near air-conditioning units that suffer from frequent condensation and mould growth. Over a period of 18 months, the Gush-coated surface showed an absolute resistance to mould growth while its surrounding areas were devastated." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/science-fiction-last-of-us/11.png", alt: "Screenshot referenced in the closing section on mould prevention" },
      { type: "heading", text: "What's the secret science?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Our paints feature 3 anti-mould features in 1. First we have the Gush Absorption Element (GAE) that absorbs and desorbs moisture from Gush-coated surfaces, keeping the surface dry. This means mould spores are deprived of moisture to germinate, and perish. Second, we have antimicrobial agents in our paint that break down mould's organic structure so they cease to exist. Finally, our Gush Proprietary Catalyst (GPC) creates a unique structural layer on the painted surface that ruptures mould microbe membranes upon contact." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "That's to say, mould has no chance. Besides that, our paints work hard in the background to ensure your air is purified of VOCs 24/7. They're anti-bacterial, toxic-free, odourless and safe." },
      { type: "heading", text: "In application." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "If you live in highly humid countries like Singapore and Hong Kong, you'd be no stranger to mould. Areas close to the coast, or with high air-conditioning usage are especially prone. Gush paints have been the go-to solution deployed in airports, co-working spaces, malls and hospitals to combat mould problems at its source. You know what they say, prevention is the best intervention." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Our paints are formulated with care and love, with the intention of not just looking good as colours on walls, but with real features that work for real people. Life can be unpredictable. We're strong believers in taking control where we can — and it starts from our homes." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "gush-guide-to-colour-theory",
    title: "Gush's guide to colour theory",
    sourceUrl: "https://santinepillay.wordpress.com/2023/07/28/gushs-guide-to-colour-theory/",
    blocks: [
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/gush-guide-to-colour-theory/1.png", alt: "Screenshot of the published colour theory article on Gush's blog" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Colour goes wall deep." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Colour is deeply personal. Positive associations for one person could be negative associations for another. Either way, one thing's for sure: colour has the ability to transform a room and affect your mood. Whether you're aiming for a cosy and inviting atmosphere or a vibrant and modern aesthetic, understanding how to pick, pair and implement colours effectively is key." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Understanding colour psychology." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Before we go straight into it, it's important to understand colour psychology. Different hues evoke distinct emotions and moods. For instance, warm colours like reds, oranges, and yellows can create a sense of energy and cosiness, while cool colours such as blues and greens promote calmness and relaxation. Consider the atmosphere you want to cultivate in each room and select colours accordingly." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Monochromatic pairings." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"Monochrome\" sounds like something dull, unexciting and one-dimensional but it's far from it. It doesn't mean grayscale or black and white. Instead, it means the use of the same colour. Different shades of the same colour also count. For instance, you could go with baby blue walls with electric blue borders. Or for subtlety, you could choose a white paint with blue undertones, and pair that with bolder shades of blue for a cohesive look." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/gush-guide-to-colour-theory/2.png", alt: "Screenshot illustrating colour psychology examples" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Colour-blocking." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Regardless of your stylistic choices, it's always good to have a colour wheel handy. Give your brain a little break, and let science take over. The colour wheel is the perfect representation of how colours relate to one another. To colour block effectively, choose colours that are opposite one another on the wheel. This gives you a bold, striking and dramatic effect with maximum contrast. These colours seemingly don't belong together, but when they are, it's pure magic." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/gush-guide-to-colour-theory/3.jpg", alt: "Colour wheel" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Some classic colour-blocking pairings include:\n– Blue and orange\n– Purple and yellow\n– Green and pink" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Complementary colours." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Grab that colour wheel. If you're set on using a green, you could pick the next 2-3 shades on either side of where green lays on the colour wheel. The results are astoundingly pleasing to the eye. This isn't limited to just wall colour, but also furniture in your space too." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/gush-guide-to-colour-theory/4.png", alt: "Screenshot illustrating complementary colour pairings" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Hello, colour expert." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Now that you're equipped with some rudimentary knowledge on picking colours – let this guide your everyday life. Don't be afraid to paint with all the colours of the rainbow – from your wall colours to your wardrobe. We all need a little colour in our life and with Gush paints, that's exactly what you'll get." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Important note: Not all Gush colours featured are available online. To gain access to our full collection of colours, engage our preferred painting services partner, Groundworks." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "vanessa-toxic-free-living",
    title: "How Vanessa created a toxic-free living space with Gush",
    sourceUrl: "https://santinepillay.wordpress.com/2023/02/07/how-vanessa-created-a-toxic-free-living-space-with-gush/",
    blocks: [
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/vanessa-toxic-free-living/1.png", alt: "Screenshot of the published Vanessa profile on Gush's blog" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Introducing: A family of 6." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "When we visited her 4-room HDB flat, Vanessa had lived in it for just 2 weeks. She'd just spent her first Lunar New Year in her newly renovated home, with her husband and 3 kids — a 5-year-old, a pair of 3-year-old twins and a 6-year-old mini Schnauzer." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "When asked what she thought about Gush paint, she summarised it in 3 points — speed, comfort and peace of mind. \"This was my second renovation. When I say there's no smell, there's really no smell at all. I was happy. I moved in faster, got comfortable faster, and it felt like I've been living here for a while. It made me feel good to move my kids in earlier. No smell, no headaches, no itchy eyes, nothing.\"" },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/vanessa-toxic-free-living/2.png", alt: "Photo of Vanessa's home referenced in the article" },
      { type: "heading", text: "A nose that stays wary." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "She feels strongly about this. With a sensitive nose, she often enters a space and smells new items before she sees them — like a new car mat. One could say her nose is her superpower. She cheekily let us in on an anecdote. \"A good friend of mine was supposed to move homes at the same time as me. Her landlord used a normal traditional paint and she still can't move in 2 – 3 weeks later, even with air-purifiers. The type of interior paint you use makes a big difference.\"" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Once bitten, twice shy." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Vanessa did not have the best experience for her first home renovation 8 years ago, beyond toxic fumes from materials like vinyl flooring, carpentry and paint. Her dog at the time had pre-existing health issues that were exacerbated by the poor air quality. This physically manifested with the tearing of the eyes and general irritation." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "More often than not, big life changes affect our worldview and how we function after. Vanessa believes that while some of her late dog's health issues were beyond her control, the best thing one can do is to keep the environment you live in clean, healthy and toxic-free. This thinking influences how she lives her life and raises her children." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Of form and function." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "If there's one thing we learnt about Vanessa, she's a minimalist. In her home, every wall and ceiling is a perfect shade of white. No accent walls. No extra colours. Consistent. Comfortable. Peaceful. When asked about her living philosophy, she described practicality. \"Things need to be functional, and they need to serve a purpose. You invest in your comfort. If your environment is in disarray, it's difficult to be in the right frame of mind to focus on what's next.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Beyond just an aesthetic, it is a lifestyle choice. \"When you have kids, you start thinking deeper about safety and reducing toxic exposure. We only use glass and metal water bottles — no plastics. Same for dishwashing liquid, laundry detergent, shower gel.\" While it may sound like quite a task, Vanessa asserts that it's not difficult to find safe products in Singapore." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/vanessa-toxic-free-living/3.png", alt: "Photo of Vanessa's home referenced in the article" },
      { type: "heading", text: "The cost of reducing formaldehyde." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Unsurprisingly wise and well-read, Vanessa knew all about the Singapore government's plans to potentially introduce formaldehyde limits in building products. \"I think it's awesome. There are studies that prove formaldehyde exposure leading to leukaemia and other cancers. For me, it's a risk I won't take. Think of it this way; the cost of managing cancer — financial, mental, emotional — is not worth it. I'd rather pay for precautions.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "However, she's also well aware of the luxury afforded by this thinking. \"For Singaporeans living paycheck to paycheck, reducing chemical exposure in their everyday lives is the last thing on their minds. If this becomes the industry standard, everyone can live with one less worry.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Besides health preservation, Vanessa has her heart out for workers who are constantly exposed to formaldehyde in their line of work. These limits, if imposed, would make a tremendous difference in their lives." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Advancements in technology." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Through her renovation experiences, she has acutely observed improvements in material technology over 8 years. \"Technology will allow us to live better lives and reduce chemical exposure. It's improving.\" She alludes this to corporation-level improvements, such as better raw materials and vacuums to eliminate pollutants. And of course, Gush's non-toxic and air-purifying paints make the list." },
      { type: "heading", text: "The simple pleasures." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "From our illuminating conversation with Vanessa, it truly feels like she has everything under control. When asked what wellness means to her, she expertly tells us about its multifaceted nature. There's good food and time spent in nature. \"It's also about being able to take a Sunday afternoon nap,\" she laughs. \"That's wellness to me. It makes me happy. It's harmonious living. Having a comfortable place to come home to, watching my kids grow up healthily and happily. It's the simple pleasures.\"" },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/vanessa-toxic-free-living/4.png", alt: "Photo of Vanessa's home referenced in the article" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "It is the simple pleasures indeed. To live a life that's a little more intentional. To pay attention to the little things — like the brand of paint — that transforms your life for the better, while being easy on the planet. Together, we can go beyond the surface." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "vikram-nair",
    title: "#PeopleOfSembawang: Mr Vikram Nair",
    sourceUrl: "https://santinepillay.wordpress.com/2018/02/02/example-post-2/",
    blocks: [
      { type: "attribution", text: "First published on Sembawang GRC's blog.", linkText: "Read the original here.", href: "https://kampungsembawang.wordpress.com/2018/02/02/peopleofsembawang-mr-vikram-nair/" },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/vikram-nair/1.jpg", alt: "Mr Vikram Nair, Member of Parliament for Sembawang GRC" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Mr Vikram hardly needs an introduction. As a Member of Parliament for Sembawang GRC since 2011, Mr Vikram has the Admiralty ward of the five-man GRC under his wing. Being a resident of his GRC for five years now, he knows the neighbourhood and residents like the back of his hand. On top of his MPs' duties, he's a partner at the law firm Rajah & Tann, and was the Vice-Chairman of Singapore's Malayalam Language Education Society. He has also served on the committees of various other non-profit societies in Singapore. To sum him up; he's a man of purpose and passion." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/vikram-nair/2.jpg", alt: "Mr Vikram Nair in Sembawang" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Juggling many duties, we managed to catch Mr Vikram right before his weekly meet-the-people session for a quick chat about his duties in the GRC, and his personal life." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "When asked about what makes Sembawang special, he remarks," },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"It has a unique combination of rich history and easy lifestyle – there are many parts of Sembawang which are old and historic, yet parts that are new. There are many young families adding to the vibrancy, along with good food. When I go to Woodlands Crescent Park, which is outside where I live, you get to see all the different generations there. You see old folks and young ones all playing together. It has a very strong community feeling.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Aside from the rich history, Sembawang is known to have a wide variety of food. When probed about his favourite spots, he cites the scenery as one of the neighbourhood's distinctive features." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I have different places for different moods. I like the place at Sembawang Park, Beaulieu House, it's quite a nice place. I enjoy places along the waterfront, or the park. I have a preference for places like that. Right now I'm a fan of Kampung Admiralty – it's so good that even people from Yishun are coming over. It's usually the other way round,\" he jokes." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Lush parks and greenery aside, Sembawang's unique Kampung Spirit captures the spirit of nostalgia for Mr Vikram." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I didn't grow up in a kampung, but I've heard a lot about the lifestyle, and I've seen it secondhand from my mother. I grew up in Bedok, but there was a kampung right next door where I would walk through to go to school. My mother had a wooden house on stilts with the zinc roof, not exactly in the kampung, but it was very kampung style.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Indeed, there's a wistfulness over the Kampung life that we can't let go off, a certain level of freedom and camaraderie. On that note, Mr Vikram adds:" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I think sometimes people romanticise the kampung life but the truth is, life is a lot better nowadays. You might miss the kampong spirit where there's a lot more goto royang and you support each other a lot more and so on. Right now what makes a difference is the public housing, flowing water and electricity. That changed lives completely, and of course, with every generation, the expectations go up as well. That's fair, because you will always want a better life than what there was before.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "A man of many duties, we were curious if he had any tips to share about the way he handles challenges that come his way. In a solemn manner, he offers:" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I don't live life by inspiring quotes but I guess I always believe that you should never run away from a problem – always deal with it.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The ability to tackle problems swiftly and effectively is critical to any MP, alongside plenty other important decisions to be made on a daily basis. He humbly shares certain aspects in which he feels he has made great leaps in." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"One of the things I think I probably will be able to make the most difference in the recent years will be public transport. When I was first appointed, the 901 bus service was one of the services that served most of my residents. There were long waiting times and that wasn't great. We liaised with LTA and worked something out to increase the number of services for that. More recently, the 912 bus service that serves residents in the Woodlands Ring Road area experienced many delays. We studied the route and found out that the delays were caused by the causeway. This required more work as the bus service went through different GRCs besides mine, but we managed to get the support of different MPs, and SMRT. Once this was done, the lives of people became remarkably better.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Other duties of an MP include participation in community and grassroots events. With a joyful spark in his eyes, Mr Vikram tells us what he enjoys most about these events." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I remember my first few events at Admiralty, particularly National Day Celebrations which always get very large number of people down. Schools get involved as well, it's nice to see young children performing. You really get a sense of the whole community. There are typically more than 2000 people who come down and have a good time.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Being an MP is not all glitz and glamour, it comes with real responsibility and hard-hitting problems that affect large groups of people. Mr Vikram thrives in difficult situations due to his positive attitude, work ethic and his genuine need to help others. He shares a troubling incident that occurred within months of his appointment." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"When I was first appointed, my first public holiday was Vesak Day and that's when we had this incident of a maid who was killed at the block. There was literally crisis management because of the water tank incident, and residents were in complete panic. We had to slowly win their confidence back and get them to calm down. It didn't help that other people would try to exploit the situation by selling water purifying devices by distributing leaflets door-to-door.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Aside from his everyday responsibilities, Mr Vikram is also a new father. We asked to recall a memorable event, he sheepishly recalls the birth of his daughter." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/vikram-nair/3.jpg", alt: "Mr Vikram Nair at a community event" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"The most recent memorable moment would be the birth of my daughter. You know, suddenly becoming a father. Of course getting married changes your life, but becoming a father changes your life even more. Before that I was quite focused on my different due dates at work and living a very disciplined life. With my daughter, things have changed considerably. She's about 20 months old now, just running around, walking around… In the past, I used to start every day by going to the gym, but now I start my day by dropping her off in school. These are some adjustments to make time for your family It gives you perspective about working parents and how they juggle different responsibilities like looking after children, and you've to remember that your parents are aging as well. These little experiences you have helps you understand what other people are going through as well. It makes me feel like I can relate to people better.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "With a schedule as packed as his, Mr Vikram tells us what a typical weekend looks like for him – a mix of family time and duties around the constituency." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"Constituency duties obviously fill up a very large part of my weekends, I would say at least half to two-thirds. The remaining one-third I'll try to spend with family and friends. I try to have at least one outing with the family, and another to visit my parents. We try to find different things to do. Now that I have a daughter, we look for activities for children as well.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "At present, Mr Vikram is a man of many talents and roles, which made us particularly curious about his childhood dreams and ambitions. He charmingly deflects the question," },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"When I was in school, I did a lot of debating. After I started work, I focused most of my time on that along with socializing. I didn't have much time for hobbies. One thing's for sure, I try and fit in regular exercise as far as possible. I believe exercise is one great way to clear the mind and keep yourself in shape at the same time.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Unsatisfied, we probed into his childhood, and learned the secret sauce behind his charisma. In between laughs, he shares:" },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/vikram-nair/4.jpg", alt: "Mr Vikram Nair portrait" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"Before debating, I was interested in superheroes. I think when I was five, I wanted to be the Incredible Hulk, and at some point I wanted to be an Afghan Hound because that was the biggest dog I saw. I was out for a walk and I saw this massive dog barking and decided I wanted to be just like that. Of course, you cannot grow up and become a dog but you know, children think anything is possible.\"" },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "ong-ye-kung",
    title: "#PeopleOfSembawang: Minister Ong Ye Kung",
    sourceUrl: "https://santinepillay.wordpress.com/2017/09/08/test-pos/",
    blocks: [
      { type: "attribution", text: "First published on Sembawang GRC's blog.", linkText: "Read the original here.", href: "https://kampungsembawang.wordpress.com/2017/09/08/peopleofsembawang-minister-ong-ye-kung/" },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/ong-ye-kung/1.jpg", alt: "Minister Ong Ye Kung, Member of Parliament for Sembawang GRC" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Many of us would be familiar with Minister Ong Ye Kung, who has been serving as a Member of Parliament for Sembawang GRC since 2015. Prior to his current stint at Sembawang, Minister Ong had previously helped in Marsiling, and has lived in various parts of Singapore; from River Valley to Toa Payoh and Yio Chu Kang. Despite having experienced the many different colours and flavours of Singapore's townships, getting to know Sembawang is a special experience." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "We recently sat down with Minister Ong for a chat about Sembawang, his duties in the GRC, as well as his personal passions." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/ong-ye-kung/2.jpg", alt: "Minister Ong Ye Kung in Sembawang" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "When asked about what makes Sembawang stand out, Minister Ong muses," },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"Historically, Sembawang is different from anywhere else. With its black and white colonial bungalows, the naval base (near Sembawang Park), the waterfront – all these are historical landmarks which show that Sembawang was important to Singapore, historically. This significance that continues to give Sembawang a special character, even today.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"The atmosphere in Sembawang is different,\" he confirms, attributing this to the neighbourhood's verdant environment." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"Physically, it has a lot more greenery and blocks are not as close together, even for the new developments. The pace here feels half a step slower, more relaxing and not as breakneck.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I think even the temperature is one degree lower (from the dense greenery),\" Minister Ong jokes." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "In a spirit befitting of its lush landscape, Sembawang is known to be a tight-knit community that's big on kampung spirit. Neighbours around Sembawang have been known to meet up at least once a month for a meal. Minister Ong offers a piece of history:" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"Mr Khaw Boon Wan told me this story – most of the older generation who live in Sembawang today were relocated from kampungs. At that time of relocation to Sembawang, they ensured that different generations got to live close by, resulting in a tight-knit community.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Reminiscing that there's nothing quite like the old kampung spirit, he remarks:" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"You now have to work extra hard just to get some kampung spirit. We talk a lot about kampungs but the truth is, it's never going to be the same. I grew up in a kampung; we were a family of farmers. You could leave your kitchen door open, and family members, farm workers, neighbours could come in to have a meal. If the food in my kitchen ran out, I could just walk into someone else's house, sit down at their kitchen and have another meal!\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "However, taking into account the significant amount of progress that has taken place in the years since, Minister Ong concedes that change is inevitable. He suggests that the modern heartlands are structured as such so that the kampung spirit can be kept flourishing." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/ong-ye-kung/3.jpg", alt: "Minister Ong Ye Kung at the Sembawang Sports and Community Hub site" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"For a city state like us, we have all races in a single block and common corridors where people see each other on a daily basis. This is a modern kampung; it's not the same as the old kampungs but it's as close as we can get.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "While it is important to preserve history, Minister Ong expressed a firm commitment to make the area as beautiful as can be, for the residents' enjoyment. He shares passionately about the upcoming Sembawang Sports and Community Hub (a community hub to be built at the old Admiral Hill, a project that he is involved in overseeing:" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I wanted to keep the history (of Admiral Hill), at the same time beautify the place and keep the trees. We counted 800 trees on the hill; planning to remove 200+ less valuable ones, and planted another 1000 — including fruit trees that are indigenous to this region. So we are not going to flatten the place to replace with facilities, but inserting facilities into the greenery.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"The facilities includes swimming pools, a hawker centre, an indoor sports hall and a polyclinic. It's a very nice and exciting project. We thought it would be nice to have lots of space for community gardening, and organize monthly farmers' market. There's a lot of things that we can do. I enjoy working on that project. It represents what Sembawang is about.\"" },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/ong-ye-kung/4.jpg", alt: "Minister Ong Ye Kung at a community event" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Minister Ong's relationship with Sembawang goes way back — to a time where CDs were still a hot commodity." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"When I was a teenager – about 17 or 18 years old – CDs were all the rage. There was this one shop that I would always go to: the Sembawang Music Store at Sembawang Shopping Centre. Although they were a small shop, they always sold CDs at a cheaper price than anywhere else, and had a wide selection. I got all my music there. I also remember there was very good Thai food in the basement that I enjoyed very much. The Thai Zhi Char has now expanded into a big stall at East Canberra, where I am the MP.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "An avid music lover, Minister Ong's interest spans a wide range of genres, although he mainly listens to English Rock. He names Eagles, Journey, Led Zeppelin, Queen and The Rolling Stones as some of his all-time favourites." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "When it comes to food, Minister Ong lists a great variety of personal indulgences tucked around Sembawang:" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"The famous White Bee Hoon originated from here. There's also good claypot rice that moved here from Upper Bukit Timah; The fish head curry at Jalan Legundi is really good too. There's quite a few good places to eat around here; it's definitely worth a food hunt.\"" },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/ong-ye-kung/5.jpg", alt: "Minister Ong Ye Kung portrait" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "As Minister for Education (Higher Education and Skills) and Advisor to Grassroots Organizations, Minister Ong is undoubtedly a busy man. We ask him what he likes to do for fun on the weekends." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I try to catch up on sleep when I can,\" Minister Ong laughs. \"I make my own relaxation, by leaving the music on while I work. I play records to break the monotony of work.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I still find time to read when I can. I'm reading this fascinating book titled 'We Have No Idea' by Jorge Cham. He makes difficult scientific concepts into simple comics, and even does YouTube videos explaining what the Higgs Boson is. In his book, he explains difficult quantum physics and relativity into simple language that a layman can easily understand.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Some may be surprised to know that Minister Ong's current work in the public service was not his childhood ambition." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I wanted to be an artist. I read comics; I drew my own comics; I'm a fan of them,\" he shares." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"I like Chinese Kung Fu comics; they are very beautifully drawn. Later on in life, I started collecting Batman comics — they have such beautiful artwork. Arkham Asylum is a classic comic book, all drawn in watercolour.\"" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "\"If I were a teenager now, and given my interest, I would have probably studied Digital Animation, and followed my interest. But the choices were not there then.\"" },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "mould-or-algae",
    title: "Mould or algae? A mini investigation of Sengkang and Punggol flats",
    sourceUrl: "https://santinepillay.wordpress.com/2023/06/27/mould-or-algae-a-mini-investigation-of-sengkang-and-punggol-flats/",
    blocks: [
      { type: "attribution", text: "Written for Gush's blog.", linkText: "Read the original here.", href: "https://gush.earth/blogs/wellness/mould-or-algae-a-mini-investigation-of-sengkang-and-punggol-flats" },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/mould-or-algae/2.png", alt: "Cover image for the mould or algae investigation" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "What's that — mould on the facade of young Sengkang and Punggol flats?! A countless number of stakeholders dropped this article in our DMs, looking for our thoughts as anti-mould advocates. We conducted our own thought experiment that revealed the complexity of this situation. Is that mould or algae? That is the question." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "At the moment, most news reports believe that these flats are affected by mould. If true, this has many implications on health, safety and the future of industry-wide materials used. The flats' condition has been attributed to poor building materials, and/or quality of paint. We know HDB uses an anti-algae paint, not an anti-mould paint. On the flip side, mould doesn't usually survive when exposed to sunlight. So which is it?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Before we go there, let's get down to basics and learn exactly why this particular scenario is unusual." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Mould vs Algae." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/mould-or-algae/1.jpg", alt: "Illustration referenced in the mould vs algae investigation" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "There are millions of mould species. Some of our first experiences with mould are food-related. That loaf of bread that you've kept for too long that now smells and looks suspicious. Mould is basically fungi that feeds on organic and inorganic matter (like bread, leaves or drywall) and thrives on surfaces with high moisture. Algae on the other hand, are plant-like organisms that self-sustain through photosynthesis. Also with millions of species, algae are everywhere from aquatic settings to pavements. An important part of the ecosystem, algae are also responsible for producing approximately 70% of oxygen in the atmosphere." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "In short, mould feeds on other matter to survive, while algae creates its own food. They are the antithesis of each other." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Characteristics of mould." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/mould-or-algae/3.jpg", alt: "Mould spores" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Generally, mould loves dark and damp places. It needs moisture, oxygen, food, warmth, and the presence of mould spores to grow. It's less common to encounter mould out in the open as UV rays from the Sun are known to destroy their DNA structure — killing them. However, there are some factors that could allow certain strains of mould to survive. It could be as simple as a layer of dust or debris, or the presence of Trichothecene, a group of toxins produced by certain types of fungi." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Characteristics of algae." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Fans of daylight, algae can grow anywhere with sunlight, water and carbon-dioxide. Algae are needed in aquariums and lakes to create a balanced ecosystem. You see them everywhere in the open — from pavements to park benches." },
      { type: "heading", text: "What do mould and algae have in common?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "They both need moisture to survive. When located near a water body like these Sengkang and Punggol flats, both mould and algae have the potential to thrive." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Sengkang and Punggol: A fascinating case." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "From a cursory look, it seems unlikely that mould has inoculated these flats considering their high exposure to UV rays. These flats tower into the sky, and are subject to weather elements like rain, heat and sunlight. These are conditions more favourable for algae growth, as compared to mould." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "With that said, HDB uses 1 coat of water-based sealer and 2 coats of algae-resistant emulsion paint on building facades. According to a recent Q&A with MND, the algae-resistant paint used contains biocide, which prohibits the growth of algae culture. The sealer and paint comply with SS579 and SS345 standards respectively." },
      { type: "heading", text: "So… is it mould or algae?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "If you've been following us thus far, you'll understand the conundrum." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Without doing tests, it is hard to ascertain the nature of the growth with just a visual assessment. While one would think mould can't grow in the presence of sunlight, we know certain strains could potentially persist." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Logically, these paints have been put through tests and should work as intended. There is no regulation for exterior paints requiring any anti-moulding features as mould presumably shouldn't be able to grow in bright places." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "At the same time, these conditions are highly favourable for algae growth." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "There is a chance that both mould and algae have occurred simultaneously, but we believe there is a higher chance that we're dealing with mostly algae. And there's definitely dirt involved in the mix too with the vertical streak marks." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Why is it important to tell the difference between mould and algae anyway?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Mould is always bad for our health. Most algae don't do much but affect aesthetics." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Some of us have minimal symptoms from breathing in microscopic mould spores lingering in the air. Those with allergies and compromised immune systems bear the brunt of mould's wrath. Symptoms range from skin irritation, red/itchy eyes, runny/stuffy nose, headaches, dizziness, and asthmatic symptoms to significant respiratory distress. Notably, a study has shown that children who grow up in mould-infested areas have lower cognitive scores than their peers, while their risk of developing asthma is higher." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "That's to say, mould should definitely be taken seriously." },
      { type: "heading", text: "How can we do better?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "For the case of the Sengkang and Punggol HDB flats, it's beyond the personal, but a building-wide challenge. If flats are indeed mouldy and not simply algae-ridden, it is inevitable for spores from the building's facade to enter homes. This leaves everything you own susceptible to mould germination and yourself to potential health effects." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Protect yourself." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "For those concerned about mould, algae or even dirt build-up, Gush has developed a suite of sustainable solutions to quell those pains." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Gush Interior Paints were put through rigorous testing for its anti-mould capabilities. Powerful microbial agents in our paint inhibit fungal growth and the porous core material prevents excess moisture build up on the surface, ensuring any mould spores don't germinate on your walls. Besides that, it works hard in the background to ensure your air is purified of VOCs 24/7. Our paints are anti-bacterial, toxic-free, odourless and safe. For those living near water bodies, Gush Care in particular has an additional humidity-control functionality that helps regulate moisture in the air." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/mould-or-algae/5.png", alt: "Gush Care air-purifying paint particles illustration" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Gush Exterior Paints have been awarded the Green Label certification, and have surpassed both the SS345 and even the coveted SS678 standards. Besides algae-resistance, our paints reflect more than 89% of incoming solar rays, protect buildings from UV rays, resists cracking, moisture and dirt, has high coverage and is free of formaldehyde. Which means buildings painted with Gush feel less warm indoors and are much more energy efficient, while the paint performs better for longer." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/mould-or-algae/4.png", alt: "Gush exterior paint colour swatch referenced in the article" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Leveraging our existing exterior paint know-how, we're currently working on a new Self-Cleaning Exterior Paint formulation that incorporates our past paint capabilities. Yup, you heard that right. The new formulation is highly hydrophobic, has extremely high Dirt Pick-Up Resistance (DPUR) and repels dust. This means any moisture-related growth have no room to germinate and any dirt streaks can be wicked away. Watch this space for more details to come." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Where do we go from here?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "HDB is conducting a study to ascertain the cause of the supposed mould problem, and to brainstorm ways to prevent future occurrences. Besides that, BCA is conducting a study on the impact of changing climatic and weather conditions on the service life of facade materials, to identify more durable facade materials and develop best practices for their maintenance." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "At Gush, we are deeply passionate about materials and how they work hard for us. We're known for our innovative interior paints that purify the air and resist mould (amongst other features). We're constantly reading and learning more about the needs of the industry. While we do carry exterior paint variants for B2B purposes, we are working tirelessly on improving our formulations. If you'd like to learn more, or help us validate our formulation thesis — reach out to us at hello@gush.earth." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "dangerous-everyday-chemical",
    title: "This dangerous everyday chemical is everywhere: how to protect yourself",
    sourceUrl: "https://santinepillay.wordpress.com/2023/06/28/this-dangerous-everyday-chemical-is-everywhere-how-to-protect-yourself/",
    blocks: [
      { type: "paragraph", text: "We live in a society full of pollutants. More often than not, we don't fully know what we're putting in, on, and around our bodies. Besides the air we breathe, there's also food, the packaging that holds them, cosmetics and personal care items, even toys, perfumes and household objects. It turns out, we're surrounded by countless chemicals that are harmful to living beings — including phthalates." },
      { type: "heading", text: "What are phthalates?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "They're a huge class of man-made chemical compounds. Since the dawn of industrialisation, these chemicals are used as plasticisers to enhance flexibility, durability and longevity of plastics; alongside solvents and personal care products. These chemicals can easily enter our bodies through inhalation, ingestion, or skin contact. They're pretty elusive and omnipresent — colourless, odourless and hard to pinpoint." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/dangerous-everyday-chemical/1.png", alt: "Screenshot of the published phthalates article on Gush's blog" },
      { type: "heading", text: "What's the problem with phthalates?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Numerous studies have been conducted showing the health implications of constant phthalate exposure. For one, they interfere with our hormones — be it male or female." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Health implication: Uterine fibroids - Non-cancerous tumours that grow in or around the uterus. Can cause pelvic and back pain, heavy menstrual bleeding etc." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Health implication: Asthma - Increased exposure to phthalates worsens pulmonary function and airway inflammation in asthmatic children." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Health implication: Attention-deficit hyperactivity diorder (ADHD) - High quantities of phthalates found in a mother's urine were associated with an increasing risk of ADHD in children." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Health implication: Type 2 diabetes - Increased phthalate levels were associated with increased insulin resistant — which controls the blood glucose levels in our cells. When this happens, it's likely a precursor to type 2 diabetes." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Health implication: Male fertility issues - Men with high concentrations of phthalates in their urine have seen lower sperm counts and poor sperm motility." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/dangerous-everyday-chemical/2.jpg", alt: "Plastic containers referenced in the article on phthalates" },
      { type: "heading", text: "How are we exposed?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "We can ingest them, inhale them, or they could get absorbed into our skin. If you use a plastic food container containing phthalates, it could leech into your food and thus get ingested in your body. Alternatively, you could potentially inhale phthalate particles lingering in the air." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/dangerous-everyday-chemical/3.jpg", alt: "Plastic products referenced in the article on phthalates" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Who is most at risk?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "While all of us are at risk, the following groups of people are most at risk:\n– Manual labourers that work closely with plastics, such as plastic manufacturing\n– Pregnant women\n– Children under the age of 3\n– Pets" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Children under the age of 3 in particular, are still developing their bodies and immune systems. They are also especially susceptible due to circumstance — with plastic toys and their oral curiosity leading to biting, chewing and sucking. Studies show that animals and pets are also at high risk — with danger to their reproductive health and other development issues." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/dangerous-everyday-chemical/4.jpg", alt: "Household plastic items referenced in the article" },
      { type: "heading", text: "How can you identify phthalates?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Sometimes it's about reading the packaging. Other times, you just need to know what to look out for." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Flexible plastics & PVC" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Phthalates are used as an additive to PVC products, which makes them flexible and elastic. If you have any flexible plastic products, chances are, they have phthalates in them unless otherwise stated as phthalate-free." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Includes: Vinyl flooring, garden hoses, shower curtains, adhesives, gloves, automobile parts, food containers." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/dangerous-everyday-chemical/5.jpg", alt: "Personal care products referenced in the article" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Containers" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "As a general rule of thumb, it's safer to use only microwave-safe containers and phthalate-free containers. Try to purchase or store your food items in glass or stainless-steel containers instead." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Avoid recycling-code-3" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "For plastic products, recycling codes are always printed on them. Take a moment to look for it, and if they're labelled with a \"3\" — they contain phthalates. Numbers 1, 2, 4 and 5 — PETE, HDPE, LDPE and PP are phthalate-free." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/dangerous-everyday-chemical/6.png", alt: "Illustration referenced in the section on Gush paints and phthalates" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Avoid \"fragrance\"." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Reading ingredient lists can be tricky. Many consumer goods make it difficult for us to identify specificities of ingredients. When the vague \"fragrance\" is listed, it's highly likely that phthalates are present. All because they help fragrances linger on your skin longer." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Includes: Nail polish, hair spray, body lotion, shampoo, conditioner, and cosmetics." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Phthalates and paints." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Besides plastics, phthalates have a history with paint too. They're added on as plasticisers that improve the paint's flexibility and durability qualities. Once the paint dries up, these plasticisers adhere to air particles. Dibutyl phthalate (DBP) is the most common phthalate in the paint industry which can cause severe health issues. It is also important to note that phthalates are not generally listed on the product label of most of the paints." },
      { type: "heading", text: "What about Gush paints?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Great news — none of our paints or paint packaging contain phthalates. Results from our SETSCO test report shows no phthalate variants present including: Dibutyl Phthalate (DBP), Benzylbutyl Phthalate (BBP), bis(2-ethylhexyl) Phthalate (DEHP), Di-n-octyl Phthalate (DNOP), Diisodecyl Phthalate (DIDP) and Diisononyl Phthalate (DINP). Our paint packaging is made out of PP plastic with recycling-code-5, which means they're not only safe, but recyclable too." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/dangerous-everyday-chemical/7.png", alt: "Gush Care air-purifying paint particles illustration" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "When it comes to non-toxicity, Gush paints are also free of heavy metals, VOCs and odour. Completely safe for pregnant women and children too. In fact, our paints were made specifically to tackle the issue of indoor air pollution. They work hard in the background to purify your air of existing VOCs from other sources in your home, without needing any additional light or electricity to be effective." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Safe for the whole family." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "At Gush, we care about built environments and those who inhabit them. Our products are created with intentional thought — keeping you safe from air pollutants with our air-purifying and anti-moulding paints. This extends to the ingredients we use too, free of phthalates, heavy metals and other harmful substances. By choosing Gush, you're reducing the release of phthalates into the environment, minimising its impact on humans and ecosystems." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "When we stay in the know about these chemicals and other pollutants around us, we can find ways to avoid or mitigate them — protecting ourselves and our loved ones too." },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "battling-the-heatwave",
    title: "Battling the heatwave: The how, what and why.",
    sourceUrl: "https://santinepillay.wordpress.com/2023/05/15/battling-the-heatwave-the-how-what-and-why/",
    blocks: [
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/battling-the-heatwave/1.png", alt: "Screenshot of the published heatwave article on Gush's blog" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "How's the weather? If you're in South or Southeast Asia, chances are you're enduring scorching heat right now. According to reports, temperatures have reached a record high to levels we haven't experienced in decades. Unfortunately, experts advise that it's only going to get worse as El Niño hits later in the year. As we battle the heatwave, let's learn a little more about what's going on, and how to cool down." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Why on Earth is it so hot?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "There are many reasons why temperatures are unusually high. There's climate change, heatwaves, the Urban Heat Island Effect and El Niño. When some of these phenomena happen at the same time, that's when it hits us the hardest." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/battling-the-heatwave/2.jpg", alt: "Photo referenced in the section on the causes of heatwaves" },
      { type: "heading", text: "The cause of heatwaves." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Heatwaves are when the weather is hotter than it should be for that period of the year, extending for two or more days. They happen when air gets trapped. Instead of cycling around the globe, air sometimes gets stuck in one place, warming up and sucking in more hot air from the atmosphere. But how does air get trapped in the first place?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "That's the result of high-pressure weather systems. This system forces air downwards and prevents it from rising. As we know, hot air is supposed to rise while cold air is supposed to sink. With this system, it traps warm air in place, preventing rain, while it just gets hotter and hotter till it finally breaks out of the system." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/battling-the-heatwave/3.png", alt: "Illustration of a high-pressure weather system" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Worsening weather: El Niño." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "We've all learned about El Niño in school when we were kids, but how much do we even remember? To recap, El Niño is basically a weather pattern that occurs when surface temperatures of the Pacific Ocean become unusually warm, leading to changes in global weather patterns. In Southeast Asia, this means hotter temperatures and less precipitation towards the tail end of the year. The last El Niño we experienced was in 2016, giving us the hottest year on record globally. Experts say that with El Niño expected to arrive again later this year or in 2024, global average temperatures are bound to be pushed beyond the 1.5 degrees Celsius threshold. That's to say, it's likely going to set a new global temperature record." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/battling-the-heatwave/4.jpg", alt: "Illustration referenced in the section on El Niño temperatures" },
      { type: "heading", text: "The Urban Heat Island Effect." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "For city dwellers, retreating to parks or rural areas can be a quick fix to escape the heat. That's because \"cities tend to be between 1 – 3 degrees Celcius warmer in the day than in the countryside.\" The reasoning is simple — Urbanisation. With more people, buildings and infrastructure, more heat is produced and retained. For example, materials like asphalt and concrete surfaces used for roads and pavements absorb heat." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/battling-the-heatwave/5.jpg", alt: "Photo referenced in the section on the Urban Heat Island Effect" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "When we experience so much day-to-day heat, we turn up our air-conditioning to stay cool. Ironically, the use of air-conditioning increases outdoor temperatures even more as units release heat outdoors. This leads to a self-perpetuating cycle of heat that's hard to escape from." },
      { type: "heading", text: "Climate change as a constant." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Heatwaves are more frequent and intense these days because of climate change. No question about it. Couple that with the Urban Heat Island Effect and El Niño, and we're reaching unprecedented temperatures." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The reality is, climate change is a man-made disaster that we've created for ourselves. The only way to alleviate it, is to take action to slow its process." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/battling-the-heatwave/6.jpg", alt: "Photo referenced in the section on climate change" },
      { type: "heading", text: "The heat can be harmful." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The heat is not just an inconvenience — these solar spectrum rays can be harmful to our health. One of the risks is exposure to ultraviolet (UV) rays, which can cause sunburn and skin cancer. On top of that, near-infrared (IR) rays, which are responsible for heat, can also be harmful in excessive amounts. Prolonged exposure to IR rays can cause skin damage, dehydration, and heat exhaustion. Finally, when we're at home, light streams in. This is known as visible light transmission, and it carries heat into our spaces too. These three always-on factors affect thermal comfort day-to-day, and get worse during a heatwave." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/battling-the-heatwave/7.jpg", alt: "Photo referenced in the section on the harmful effects of heat" },
      { type: "heading", text: "How can we stay chill?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "According to the WHO, \"it's recommended to stay indoors as much as possible during a heatwave, stay in the shade and avoid strenuous physical activity.\" Stay hydrated, take cool showers and wear light and loose materials made of natural materials like cotton." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "The WHO also recommends that indoor temperatures should be kept below 32 degrees Celsius in the day, and 24 degrees celsius at night — especially for infants or the elderly with chronic health conditions." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/battling-the-heatwave/8.jpg", alt: "Photo referenced in the section on staying cool" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Staying cool doesn't have to be expensive." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "For those of us who are acutely aware of our every action and how it impacts our planet, the struggle is real. Staying cool means cranking up that air-conditioning but doing that contributes to UHI and climate change too. Now what?" },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "As passionate advocates for wellness, sustainability and the environment, we at Gush have developed solar window films — Gush ClearCool. These thin films glide onto the inside of your windows like a screen protector would. Functionally, they work just like sunscreen for your windows. These films come in a variety of tints — from full transparency to high privacy. At its most transparent, it allows 76% of light in, ensuring your window view is as crystal clear as ever. All while blocking out 99% of harmful UV rays and 96% of IR rays — protecting your skin from the burn, your body from the heat, and your furniture from discoloration. It's sunscreen, but better. With Gush ClearCool, staying indoors feels guilt-free with up to 14.45% reduction of cooling-related energy consumption." },
      { type: "image", src: "assets/images/writing/content/battling-the-heatwave/9.png", alt: "Gush ClearCool solar window film product illustration" },
      { type: "heading", text: "Closing notes." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Get nerdy with us — read all about the tests we've put Gush ClearCool through to achieve these astounding results. Or if you're fascinated by how these thin films can achieve so much, learn more about the scientific technology that went into its inception." },
      { type: "paragraph", text: "Start your journey towards a cooler home – enquire about Gush ClearCool here." },
    ],
  },
];
